        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2583119197" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4719499743723170670">I’ve read three other books in this Mrs. Pollifax series and loved them. Unfortunately, this one doesn’t quite match the others in quality. The story seems to drag and there isn’t much spark and spunk in any of the characters. It’s not a bad read, just I was expecting much more. In this story, Mrs. Pollifax, a garden club member and grandmother, has become quite an accomplished CIA agent. She has now remarried, having been a widow for some years. Her new husband is a retired judge she met during</span>
  <span id="freeText4719499743723170670" style="display:none">I’ve read three other books in this Mrs. Pollifax series and loved them. Unfortunately, this one doesn’t quite match the others in quality. The story seems to drag and there isn’t much spark and spunk in any of the characters. It’s not a bad read, just I was expecting much more. In this story, Mrs. Pollifax, a garden club member and grandmother, has become quite an accomplished CIA agent. She has now remarried, having been a widow for some years. Her new husband is a retired judge she met during one of her adventures I haven’t read yet. She is also now very good at Karate as well as handling a weapon. Basically, she is no longer the innocent widow looking for some adventure. Her ex-CIA agent pal Farrell has gotten into trouble in Sicily, and sends for Mrs. Pollifax to help him. Luckily a young (26 year old) female CIA agent, Kate Rossiter, also happens to be vacationing on Sicily and is able to help Mrs. P. and Farrell. Also fortunately, Kate’s Aunt lives very near where Farrell is seeking help. …So there are several car chases up steep winding roads, a visiting assassin, art forgery, and the elusive prize of Julius Caesar’s signature. If you haven’t read a Mrs Pollifax mystery before … This is not the one to start with. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4719499743723170670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


